{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493387"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1308"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1308"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.68,0.01,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1308"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"12363"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless swelling in her neck. She has a family history of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis but no significant medical history herself. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1.5 cm firm swelling in the left lobe of the thyroid gland. There is no cervical lymphadenopathy. Her thyroid function tests show TSH 0.89 mIU/L (0.5-4.0), free T4 17 pmol/L (10-25). Ultrasound confirms a 16 mm solid nodule with ill-defined borders in an otherwise normal-looking thyroid gland. Fine needle aspiration cytology of the nodule shows large thyrocytes with an abnormal nucleus and cytoplasm with several mitoses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Early Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis","Multinodular goitre","Thyroid carcinoma","Early Graves\u0027 disease","Thyroid adenoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is highly likely given the solitary thyroid nodule with irregular borders and the FNA findings. The presence of large thyrocytes with abnormal nuclei and multiple mitoses on cytology strongly suggests malignancy. If thyroid scintigraphy was performed, low iodine uptake (cold nodules) would further suggest malignancy. On histological examination of thyroid tissue, Psammoma bodies and cells with Orphan Annie eyes are pathognomonic of papillary thyroid carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E fits the clinical description of a solitary thyroid nodule and ultrasound findings of a solid mass in an otherwise normal-looking thyroid. Normal thyroid function tests further support this. However, FNA cytology reveals that this lesion is unlikely to be benign, given the presence of abnormal nuclei and mitotic figures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually asymptomatic; signs of hypothyroidism are usually seen in later stages of disease progression. At this stage, changes in the thyroid gland would manifest as symmetrical enlargement, rather than a single nodule as in this case. While the patient has a family history of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis, the cytological findings are inconsistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultinodular goitre\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given that there is only a single nodule found, and there are no signs of hyperthyroidism. Multinodular goitre typically presents with multiple nodules of varying sizes throughout the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly Graves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with a triad of exophthalmos, pretibial myxedema, and diffusely enlarged goitre (with possible bruit heard on auscultation). Although it is fairly uncommon for a case to present with all three findings, in this case none of these findings are present, making this diagnosis unlikely. Graves\u0027 disease also typically presents with hyperthyroidism and suppressed TSH levels, which are not seen in this patient who has normal thyroid function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A thyroid nodule with irregular borders and atypical FNA findings is highly suggestive of thyroid carcinoma.","Thyroid function tests may be normal in early thyroid disease or thyroid carcinomas.","Cytological features such as abnormal nuclei and mitotic figures are key indicators of malignancy in thyroid nodules."],"references":["Thyroid Disorders [published 2019 June]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {accessed 1 Dec 2022}. https://www.tg.org.au","Gharib H, Papini E, Garber JR, Duick DS, Harrell RM, Hegedus L, et al. American Association of Clinical Endocrinologists, American College of Endocrinology, and Associazione Medici Endocrinologi Medical Guidelines for Clinical Practice for the Diagnosis and Management of Thyroid Nodules - 2016 Update Appendix. Endocrine Practice. 2016 May;22:1\u201360. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27167915/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1308"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T08:19:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T08:21:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1308"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"po